'''Gloria Daisy Wekker''' (born June 13, 1950) is an [[Afro-Surinamese]] Dutch educator and writer who has focused on gender studies and sexuality in the Afro-Caribbean region and diaspora. She was the winner of the Ruth Benedict Prize from the [[American Anthropological Association]] in 2007.

==Biography==
Gloria Wekker was born in 1950 in [[Paramaribo]], Suriname.<ref name="Surinam Stars">{{cite web|title=Gloria Wekker|url=http://www.surinamstars.com/Gloria%20Wekker.html|publisher=Surinam Stars|accessdate=10 February 2016|location=Paramaribo, Suriname|language=Dutch|date=2005}}</ref> She moved to [[Amsterdam]] in the 1970s and became active in the Afro-European Women’s Movement.<ref name="Encyclopedia">{{cite web|last1=Pesole|first1=Betta|title=Gloria Wekker|url=http://www.encyclopediaofafroeuropeanstudies.eu/encyclopedia/gloria-wekker/|work=Encyclopedia of Afro-European Studies|accessdate=10 February 2016|location=Universidad de León, León, Spain|date=2011}}</ref> Wekker earned a master's degree in [[cultural anthropology]]<ref name="Surinam Stars" /> from the [[University of Amsterdam]] in 1981 and began her career working in various governmental agencies in Amsterdam, such as the Ministry of Health, Welfare and Culture on Ethnic Minorities' Affairs and the Ministry of Social Affairs and Employment. In 1984, she became a founding member of "Sister Outsider", an Amsterdam-based, literary circle for lesbian black women named after the work by [[Audre Lorde]]. In 1987, she served as a Policy Associate in the Office for the Coordination of Ethnic Minorities' Affairs.<ref name="Encyclopedia" />

In 1992, Wekker earned her doctorate at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] with a thesis on the sexuality and subjectivity of Afro-Surinamese women. In 2001, she was appointed to the Aletta-chair of the Department of Women's Studies at the [[Utrecht University]].<ref name="Surinam Stars" /><ref name="Dialogo Global">{{cite web|title=9th Annual Summer School on Black Europe|url=http://www.dialogoglobal.com/amsterdam/people.php|publisher=Dialogo Global|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref><ref name="UWI">{{cite web|title=Gloria Wekker|url=https://sta.uwi.edu/crgs/november2009/gloriawekker.asp|publisher=The University of the West Indies|accessdate=11 February 2016|location=St Augustine, Trinidad and Tobago}}</ref> Her work focuses on the intersections of [[colonialism]], racism, [[white privilege]], feminist theory, lesbian theory and women in the Caribbean.<ref name="Duke Press">{{cite web|title=White Innocence: Paradoxes of Colonialism and Race|url=https://www.dukeupress.edu/white-innocence|publisher=Duke University Press|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Batra|2011|p=155}} Her work has earned her the title of "Holland’s [[Angela Davis]]"<ref name="Neilson, 2014">{{cite news|last1=Neilson|first1=Zoe|title=For Pete's sake|url=http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/pete%E2%80%99s-sake|accessdate=11 February 2016|work=[[The Voice (newspaper)|The Voice]]|date=7 December 2014|location=London, England}}</ref> as she has forced the Dutch to examine their alleged ingrained stereotypes and attitudes towards racism and patriarchy.<ref name="De Wereld Morgen">{{cite news|last1=Wekker|first1=Gloria|title=Acht wetenschappelijk onderbouwde argumenten tegen Zwarte Piet|work=De Wereld Morgen |date=23 October 2014|location=Antwerp, Belgium|language=Dutch}}</ref> She has led debate which questioned the racist nature of such iconic images in Dutch tradition as [[Santa|Sinterklaas]] (Santa Clause)'s helpers as [[blackface]] [[golliwogs]] known as ''Zwarte Piet'' (Black Pete),<ref name="Neilson, 2014" /><ref name="ten Broeke, 2014">{{cite news|last1=ten Broeke|first1=Asha|title=Zwarte Piet|url=http://www.utnieuws.nl/opinie/60711/Zwarte_Piet|accessdate=11 February 2016|work=UT Nieuws |date=11 November 2014|location=University of Twente, Enschede, Netherlands}}</ref> as well as the imagery of what constitutes beauty.<ref name="Julen, 2013">{{cite news|last1=Julen|first1=Jeannine|title='Kroes gaan' is een hele stap|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4328/Opinie/article/detail/3546096/2013/11/17/Kroes-gaan-is-een-hele-stap.dhtml|accessdate=11 February 2016|publisher=de Verdieping Trouw|date=17 November 2013|location=Amsterdam, The Netherlands|language=Dutch}}</ref>

Wekker was nominated in 2004 for the Dutch Scientific Research Council's "Triomfprijs" (Triumph prize).<ref name="Encyclopedia" /> In 2006, her book ''The Politics of Passion: Women's Sexual Culture in the Afro-Surinamese Diaspora'' won critical praise<ref name="review The Politics of Passion">{{cite web|title=Book review: Gloria Wekker, ''The Politics of Passion: Women's Sexual Culture in the Afro-Surinamese Diaspora''|url=http://fty.sagepub.com/content/9/1/119.extract|publisher=Sage Publications|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref> and was awarded with the 2007 Ruth Benedict Prize from the American Anthropological Association.<ref name="Dialogo Global" /><ref name="Utrecht">{{cite web|title=Gloria Wekker|url=http://cfhutrecht2013.com/the-colonial-legacy-conference/speakers-2/gloria-wekker/|publisher=Colofon Utrecht University|accessdate=10 February 2016|location=Utrecht, the Netherlands}}</ref> In 2011, she began a sabbatical to work at the Netherlands Institute for Advanced Studies on a research project,<ref name="Encyclopedia" /> which resulted in the publication in 2016 of ''White Innocence: Paradoxes of Colonialism and Race''.<ref name="Duke Press" /> Because of her work with both sociology and policy, Wekker has been named as part of an international committee which was appointed at the University of Amsterdam in 2015 to increase diversity at the university.<ref name="Science Guide">{{cite news|title=Westerveld gaat UvA democratiseren (''"[Lisa] Westerveld will democratize Amsterdam University"'')|url=http://www.scienceguide.nl/201511/westerveld-gaat-uva-democratiseren.aspx|accessdate=11 February 2016|work=Science Guide|date=19 November 2015|location=Amsterdam, The Netherlands|language=Dutch}}</ref>

